  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"Phase diversity-based wavefront sensing for fluorescence microscopy\" has garnered attention within the academic community, receiving 22 citations since its availability on bioRxiv. The research behind this work demonstrates significant contributions to the field of microscopy and has subsequently passed peer review, with a formal published version in the journal Optica.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This research has laid the groundwork for advancements in wavefront sensing techniques applicable to fluorescence microscopy, indicating its relevance across various institutions, including the Howard Hughes Medical Institute and the National Institutes of Health. The multi-institution affiliation reflects strong collaborative efforts in this technical domain, exemplifying the collective investment in innovative microscopy methods crucial for biomedical imaging.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The paper has been well-received, as evidenced by its 22 citations, showcasing active engagement from the scientific community. Notably, it has influenced subsequent research, indicated by 23 instances of proven downstream reuse, reflecting its utility and relevance in ongoing studies. This level of engagement points to the work's foundational significance and its role in propelling future innovations.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Moreover, the transition from preprint to formal publication underscores the importance of open science practices. The authors have successfully navigated peer review, leading to a published version that has already accrued additional citations (20), indicating a growing recognition of the research and its impact across the field.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, the study not only advances the technical aspects of fluorescence microscopy but also exemplifies effective research collaboration across prominent institutions. Its influence within the scientific community, along with robust citation metrics, illustrates a strong foundation for further exploration and innovation in optical technologies.</p>",
